[2] USA - 5th WNV-positive bird in California
Date: Tue 8 Feb 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Santa Clarita Daily News, Tue 8 Feb 2005 [edited]
<http://www.dailynews.com/Stories/0,1413,200~20949~2698033,00.html>


USA: 5th confirmed West Nile virus-positive bird in California
--------------------------------------------------------------
A dead crow found in Valencia has tested positive for West Nile virus
(WNV), officials said on Mon 7 Feb 2005, making it the 3rd confirmed
infection statewide so far this year [2005]. The Greater Los Angeles
County Vector Control District confirmed that the Valencia crow,
picked up on Thursday [3 Feb 2005] by the county Department of Animal
Care and Control, tested positive for the virus on Friday. It was the
1st infected bird found in Los Angeles County so far this year.
Elsewhere in the state, one infected crow was picked up from Santa
Clara County, while another was found in Sonoma County.

Vector control and health experts said it was too early to tell
whether the discoveries mean the rate of infection in Southern
California will be the same this year [2005] as last year. Infected
dead crows are often the 1st sign that WNV is in the area. "It's hard
to say why this bird was infected at this time," said Vector Control
spokeswoman Stephanie Miladin. "Last year [2004], we started seeing
them in early March." State health officials said the early
discoveries come as no surprise. California is one of few states that
conducts year-round mosquito surveillance.

"What we experienced in 2004 was that basically we had transmissions
every month starting in February," said Stan Husted, supervising
public health biologist for the state's Department of Health
Services. "We know that we've got West Nile transmission year-round.
Typically, it's really hard to make any predictions, but we know
we're going to have West Nile activity. We know that the 2nd year in
an area is worse than the 1st year. For those areas that have WNV for
the 1st time, we expect there's going to be more activity."

The virus 1st appeared in New York in 1999, and it has since moved
westward, blanketing the nation. According to health experts, WNV is
spread to humans from the bite of an infected mosquito. Mosquitoes
are infected by biting a bird that carries the virus. Most mosquitoes
do not carry the virus, and most people bitten by a mosquito do not
become infected with WNV. The virus is not contagious among humans,
health officials have emphasized. Those who are infected do not
become sick in most cases. But if they do, symptoms include fever,
headache, nausea, body aches and mild skin rashes, health officials
said. California saw its 1st WNV human fatality in 2003. Last year
[2004], there were a total of 828 people infected with WNV from 23
counties statewide. There have been 27 deaths to date in California
from Kern, Los Angeles, Orange, Riverside, San Bernardino and Tehama
counties.

"It will be a while, maybe several years, before West Nile virus dies
down to low levels," Husted said, adding that the state vector
control agencies have worked to keep mosquito populations down, which
may help in the summer months. This year [2005], state health
officials will collect fewer crows, but will ask the public's help in
reporting dead birds by posting sightings on
<http://www.westnile.ca.gov>.
"That's what's going to give us a lot of information," Husted said.

In the meantime, health officials are encouraging residents to
continue taking the same precautions as in the summer months, such as
eliminating sources of standing water where mosquitoes are likely to
lay eggs; using insect repellent containing DEET; avoiding areas with
mosquitoes, especially around dusk and dawn; and securing window
screens that may have holes.

[Byline: Susan Abram]

