******
[3] USA - 1st (suspected) human case in California
Date: Wed 9 Feb 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmai.org>
Source: napanews.com, Associated Press report, Wed 9 Feb 2005 [edited]
<http://tinyurl.com/6pcp9>


USA: 1st suspected West Nile virus human case of 2005 in California
-------------------------------------------------------------------
The 1st human case of West Nile virus in Los Angeles County this year
[2005] was reported on Tue 8 Feb 2005, months before the
mosquito-borne illness usually appears and prompting health officials
to remind people to take precautions. An elderly man, who resides in
the eastern part of the county, is recovering after he was
hospitalized with fevers and altered consciousness, said Dr. Jonathan
Fielding, health officer for the county Department of Health Services.

Fielding said a bird infected with the mosquito-borne virus was
reported on Mon 7 Feb 2005, but it was unknown whether the bird was
the source of the man's infection. The man, whose identity was
withheld to protect his privacy, was infected near his home. "I don't
think we should be alarmed," Fielding said, referring to a possible
repeat of last year's [2004] outbreak that infected more than 800
people and killed 27 statewide. "We can have sporadic cases ... We
have to assume that we're going to have a serious problem, and we
like to be surprised."

The case could be the 1st human case in California this year [2005],
but it has not been confirmed by the state Department of Health
Services, said spokesman Robert Miller. In Los Angeles County, which
had the most cases of any of California's 58 counties, 329 people
were infected and 13 died from the virus. West Nile virus 1st
appeared in California in 2003 and infected 3 people in Southern
California. Health officials said the worst outbreaks usually occur
in the 2nd year in many states. In Colorado, for example, nearly 3000
people were infected and 63 people died in 2003, the 2nd year of the
outbreak.

Ken Fujioka, assistant manager of the San Gabriel Valley Mosquito and
Vector Control District, said the recent storms and warm evening
temperatures may contribute to the spread of the virus. "We're
worried that any time it gets warm during the winter, there's that
potential for mosquitoes," he said.

[Byline: Chris T. Nguyen]

